    "Let me analyze this reaction to identify the roles of reagents, solvent, and catalyst.\n\nLooking at the reaction SMILES:\n- Reactants: CO, Cl, NHc1ccccc1 (benzylamine), O=CCO[cyclodextrin], [BH3-]C#N, [Na+]\n- Product: cyclodextrin with -OCH2CH2NHCH2Ph group (reductive amination product)\n\nThe reaction is a reductive amination where:\n1. The aldehyde (O=CCO- on cyclodextrin) reacts with the amine (NH2CH2Ph, benzylamine) to form an imine\n2. The imine is then reduced by NaBH3CN (sodium cyanoborohydride)\n\nNow let me assign roles:\n- **NaBH3CN** ([BH3-]C#N.[Na+]): This is the reducing agent (reagent) - it reduces the imine intermediate\n- **Benzylamine** (NCc1ccccc1): This is a reagent - it's the amine nucleophile that reacts with the aldehyde\n- **Aldehyde-functionalized cyclodextrin** (O=CCO[cyclodextrin]): This is the substrate/reagent\n- **MeOH** (CO): This is the solvent - methanol is commonly used as solvent in reductive amination\n- **HCl** (Cl): This is a catalyst/acid additive - reductive amination with NaBH3CN typically requires mildly acidic conditions (pH ~6-7) to protonate the imine and make it more electrophilic for reduction while keeping NaBH3CN stable\n\nSo the role mapping:\n- CO (methanol): solvent\n- Cl (HCl): catalyst (acid catalyst for imine formation)\n- NCc1ccccc1 (benzylamine): reagent\n- O=CCO[cyclodextrin] (aldehyde-cyclodextrin): reagent (substrate)\n- [BH3-]C#N.[Na+] (NaBH3CN): reagent (reducing agent)\n\nLet me format this as a condition_role_mapping."
